    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-18T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-18T05:00:00-05:00" n="392"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d392">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C115/1413: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tittmann</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-18T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 18, 1940—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 19—1:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>92. For State and Labor from Commissioner and Consul:</p>
                <p>Commissioner expresses appreciation for telegram No. 64, June 15, 5 p.m.,<note
                        n="17" xml:id="d392fn17">Not printed.</note> indicating prompt attention to
                    question raised in our telegram No. 90 of June 14.</p>
                <p>No recommendation was included in the cable transmitting the Winant request. The
                    Commissioner in the present message urges the most favorable possible
                    consideration of the request. Present circumstances in his judgment demonstrate
                    that the transfer of ILO staff to the United States offers the one promising
                    chance of preserving the organization as a functioning democratic institution.
                    Unless a decision can be reached before armistice terms are settled it may
                    become very much more difficult if not impossible to transfer most valued
                    members of the staff.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tittmann</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
